==English==

===Etymology===
Attested in the 13th Century {{C.E.}}; from ''[[clergie]]'', from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|clergié||learned men|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|clericātus||lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|clericus||one ordained for religious services|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|κληρικός|sc=polytonic|tr=klērikos||of the clergy|lang=grc}}.

